The extinct species cannot re-enter the community, therefore, due to the stochasticity of the system, the community will eventually randomly lose all species but one.

Question 12

Explain what you found from this plot about the effect of initial conditions. Why does the neutral model simulation give you those particular results?

When a community is simulated by the neutral model with the same rate of speciation, there is likely to have a dynamic equilibrium. There is no obvious impact of the initial states of richness, because the chances of extinction and speciation are the same in both populations. However, the model with speciations prevents the mono-dominance from persisting as new species can occur in both scenarios. Regardless of initial values, evaluate the speciation rate and numbers of individuals, and they would converge to a dynamic equilibrium with similar pattern.

Feedback

Good answer and explanation, although a little roundabout! Watch out for grammar and readability. The only problem is that the figure legend is a little misleading; what does initial minimum population mean? That the population size is minimum? What is the accurate statement here to describe this initial condition? (Use the word community rather than population, and make sure you include the key word differentiating the two conditions).

Question 16

Does the initial condition of the system matter? Why is this?

The initial richness of the system does not affect the final results. As the speciation rate is equal to all the simulated community in the neutral model, the species abundance follows a Poisson distribution shape. Therefore, no matter the initial richness is, the system tends to have the same trends and get a dynamic equilibrium.

Feedback

Very nice graphs except that the titles do not helpfully explain what the different initial conditions were.

Your answer has some good thoughts in, but does not effectively explain why the initial conditions do not affect the observed octaves. Also, be careful to be accurate - it is not true that the neutral model octaves follow a Poisson distribution (although they may look similar).

Question 25

How does the initial distribution of the population in different life stages affect the initial and eventual population growth?

The initial distribution of the population in different life stages can affect the initial and eventual population growth. For example, a population with a large proportion of individuals in the reproductive age range is more likely to have a higher growth rate than a population with a smaller proportion of individuals in this age range.

Feedback

Good - but why? Try to be more explicit. Also, this is a deterministic model, so whether things are more or less likely is not important. We know exactly what is going to happen!

The graph and code are great.

Question 33

How does the smoothness of the earlier deterministic simulations compare with these stochastic simulations? Why?

The earlier deterministic simulations were smooth, while the stochastic simulations are more jagged. This is because the deterministic simulations assumed a fixed number of clutches each time step, while the stochastic simulations randomly selected the number of clutches from a given distribution.

Feedback

Very good understanding! Your explanation is a little inaccurate - for example, the number of clutches each time step is not fixed in the deterministic model - but it is determined rather than random. Also, note that survival and maturation are also drawn randomly from a distribution as well as recruitment.

Challenge Question A

Fantastic! The only coding issue is that you used the value of 0.972 as p in the input to qnorm, which is the equivalent to doing a one-tailed rather than two-tailed test. Can you think of how to modify this?

Overall the graphs looks good. However, your graph titles are not very helpful, and it is not clear what the different lines are that have been plotted; you should make it clear which is the mean line/confidence intervals, and what the other line means. Finally, the mean species richness value is not actually clear from the plot (it is covered up by the confidence interval bars and the simulation line) - and this was the main point of the question.

Challenge Question D

How many CPU hours were used on the coalescence simulation and how many on the cluster to do an equivalent set of simulations? Why were the coalescence simulations so much faster?

as.numeric(proc.time()[3] - ptm) seconds were taken for Coalescence simulations (200 repeats), but an analogous set of simulations on the cluster required a total of 11.5 hours to run (11.5 hrs for each of 100 simulations). Only those lineages that are present in the final community are simulated, which makes the coalescence simulations so much faster. However, the conclusions from the two approaches are comparable and with no obvious differences.

Feedback

Excellent code and answer, and the graphs are nice! Just a few issues. Firstly, you were asked to produce a graph to compare the coalescence model and your cluster simulation - but your graph only shows the coalescence calculations. Secondly, you have only generated 200 data points using the coalescence model - which is not equivalent to the cluster runs which generated many more data points than this. On the graphs, I would have liked the octave classes to be labelled.

## Marks awarded: 8/10

Challenge Question E

How do the two simulations differ in terms of the initial behaviour of the graph of mean life stage against time? Why?

Initial conditions 1 which contains 100 adults has been maintained at a stable level, but Initial conditions 2 which evenly spread has experienced an increasing trend. In the first condition, with a population of 100 adults, the mean life stage will initially be at the final life stage (adulthood) because there are no individuals in any of the other life stages. The graph of mean life stage against time will start at a constant value of the final life stage and remain there unless there is a change in the population size or life stage distribution. In the second condition with a population of 100 individuals spread across the four life stages, the mean life stage will be a weighted average of the proportions of individuals in each life stage. The graph of mean life stage against time will depend on how the proportions of individuals in each life stage change over time.

Feedback

The graph and code are correct, and there are some good ideas in the text. However, you have misread the graph; the entirely adult population does decrease in terms of mean life stage - Im not sure why you felt it stayed the same. This question was looking for you to explain and understand the dynamics shown on your graph.
